caption.text:
Air Canada has suspended all flights to Cuba, effective immediately, citing an ongoing aviation fuel shortage across the island that is expected to worsen starting Feb. 10. The airline says it will operate empty flights southbound over the next few days to bring back roughly 3,000 travellers currently in Cuba, while tankering extra fuel and making technical stops if needed to safely complete return trips.⁠
⁠
Air Canada is also rolling out flexible rebooking and automatic refund policies for impacted customers, including those booked through Air Canada Vacations, who will receive support through local representatives. Meanwhile, WestJet and Air Transat say they are still operating flights using contingency measures, as Canada’s updated travel advisory warns of worsening shortages of fuel, electricity, and basic necessities in Cuba that could disrupt travel on short notice.⁠
⁠

Elon Musk and Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang argue that in the age of artificial intelligence, students should focus more on learning physics and mathematics instead of spending all their time on coding.

Both leaders believe programming is becoming easier and more automated through AI tools, while fundamental subjects like problem solving, logic, and deep scientific thinking remain irreplaceable foundations for real innovation.

Musk echoed the same idea, saying that true breakthroughs come from mastering the basics of science and engineering, not just learning specific programming languages that machines may soon handle on their own.

caption.text:
A planned alternative halftime lineup from Turning Point USA drew widespread mockery after the far-right group revealed its performers ahead of the 2026 Super Bowl. 

Turning Point USA, a billionaire-funded psy-op that constantly pushes culture war topics to divide Americans, announced it would host an “All-American Halftime Show” as a counter to the NFL’s choice of having a brown, Spanish-singing American, Bad Bunny, as the Super Bowl halftime headliner.

The group’s roster was an all-white lineup, including Kid Rock, Brantley Gilbert, Lee Brice and Gabby Barrett.

But footage from inside Donald Trump’s Super Bowl viewing party showed something different: instead of watching Turning Point’s broadcast, screens at the event were tuned to Bad Bunny’s official halftime show. ￼

That image quickly spread online, with critics calling it hypocritical — given the right’s vocal complaints about Bad Bunny and advocacy for the TPUSA alternative. Some commentators suggested it highlighted a disconnect between conservative outrage and what people actually chose to watch. ￼

Bad Bunny’s halftime performance — a vibrant set that celebrated Puerto Rican culture and drew massive viewership — continued despite backlash, including from Trump, who later criticized it as “absolutely terrible” on social media. ￼

Meanwhile, the Turning Point USA broadcast reportedly attracted only a tiny fraction of that audience, even as organizers tout viewership figures.

data.accessibility_caption: Photo by William Copus on February 08, 2026. May be a Twitter screenshot of poster, magazine and text that says 'THEFEEDSK TAYLOR SWIFT ONCE HELD AN ONLINE CONTEST TO PERFORM AT ANY HIGH SCHOOL IN THE USA. ONLINE TROLLS HIJACKED THE AND CHOSE A SCHOOL FOR THE DEAF. (Read post description for the details)'.

caption.text:
This is the exact reason why you never let the internet vote on anything. Luckily, this actually ended well.

In 2012, Taylor Swift partnered with Papa John's for a contest. She promised to perform a live concert at whichever school in the country got the most online votes.

It was supposed to be a fun PR stunt for high schoolers.

But... The internet got involved.

Trolls decided it would be hilarious to send a world-famous singer to the one place where nobody could actually hear her music.

They started a massive campaign to vote for the Horace Mann School for the Deaf in Boston.

Within days, the school skyrocketed to the number one spot.

Obviously, Taylor and the sponsors were in a huge bind. They couldn't actually go through with the concert because it would look like they were mocking the students.

So, they compromised. Taylor didn't perform, but she and the sponsors donated $50,000 to the school's music program.

She also gave every single student a free ticket to her next local show.

caption.text:
Bruce Willis’ wife, Bruce Willis and caregiver Emma Heming Willis, has shared a touching update on his health amid his battle with frontotemporal dementia (FTD). Speaking publicly, she revealed that Willis remains unaware of his diagnosis — a result of a neurological condition called anosognosia that prevents him from recognizing his own cognitive decline. Despite the progression of the disease, she said he still recognizes his loved ones and remains “present in his body,” a detail she described as both a blessing and a curse.

The family’s journey began with Willis’ retirement from acting in 2022 following an aphasia diagnosis, which later evolved into FTD. Emma has spoken candidly about caregiving challenges, emphasizing how the couple’s daughters and extended family continue to share meaningful connections with the actor even as his condition progresses. Her comments highlight not just the reality of life with dementia but the ways in which love and familiarity can persist in the face of neurological change. ￼

caption.text:
Starting this week, U.S. travelers flying domestically are required to present a REAL ID compliant driver’s license or an approved alternative such as a passport at airport security checkpoints. The change follows the federal enforcement of the REAL ID Act, which sets stricter identification standards for air travel.

Passengers without a REAL ID may still be allowed to fly but should expect additional screening. This process can include identity verification, extra security checks, and longer wait times at TSA checkpoints. Officials advise arriving earlier than usual if a REAL ID is not available.

The REAL ID program was created to enhance security standards nationwide, and officials recommend travelers confirm their identification status before arriving at the airport to avoid delays or complications.

Source: Transportation Security Administration

caption.text:
A North Carolina man was charged in a large-scale music streaming fraud case tied to AI.

Prosecutors say he used AI tools to generate hundreds of thousands of songs, uploaded them to streaming platforms, and then used automated programs to stream those tracks billions of times. The activity made it look like real people were listening, allowing him to collect more than $10 million in royalty payments that should have gone to real artists.

Federal authorities charged him with wire fraud, conspiracy to commit wire fraud, and money laundering conspiracy. Each charge carries a potential sentence of up to 20 years in prison.

The case highlights a growing issue for digital platforms. Cheap content generation combined with automation can overwhelm systems built on trust and scale. As AI music gets cheaper and easier to produce, platforms will need better ways to separate real demand from automated noise.
